PG  - 277-9
AB  - A severe nutritional deficiency status is described in a 22-year-old patient with
      Crohn's disease. The clinical picture on admission was dominated by an episode of
      gastrointestinal bleeding secondary to clotting disturbances (vitamin K
      deficiency) and severe cachexia due to a protein energy malnutrition. The
      mechanisms of severe nutritional disturbances in Crohn's disease are
      multifactorial. In this patient, lymphatic leakage into the intestinal lumen was 
      a major contributing factor in the pathogenesis of protein-losing enteropathy,
      fat malabsorption, and lymphocytopenia. The authors were able to demonstrate this
      intestinal lymph loss by nuclear imaging.
