      was determined at d 0 (postabsorptive), 7, 14 (during full enteral nutrition) and
      15 (postabsorptive). Resting energy expenditure was not significantly different
      between patients and controls, whereas the respiratory quotient (RQ) was lower in
      patients (0.78 +/- 0.05 vs. 0.86 +/- 0.05; P < 0.05). During enteral nutrition in
      7 patients with Crohn's disease, the RQ increased on d 7 compared with d 0 and
      remained high even after cessation of enteral nutrition (d 0, 0.78 +/- 0.03; d 7,
      0.91 +/- 0.04; d 15, 0. 84 +/- 0.05; P < 0.05; d 7 and 15 vs. d 0). No effects of
      enteral nutrition on resting energy expenditure were found. Active Crohn's
      disease is associated with changes in substrate metabolism that resemble a
      starvation pattern. These changes appear not to be specific to Crohn's disease
      but to malnutrition and are readily reversed by enteral nutrition. Enteral
      nutrition did not affect resting energy expenditure. Wasting is a consequence of 
      malnutrition but not of hypermetabolism in Crohn's disease.
